english:
  title: A Letter to Privy Councillor Kwon, Sent on Behalf of Yi Dam-ji
  author: Lim Chun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I bow my head in reverence and kneel twice before you.

    With the first winter's harsh cold upon us, I gaze upward in admiration at your path of virtue, pure and sublime. Though unworthy, I have received your grace and remain in good health. Last autumn, when the monk Junggun came to the capital, he spoke of your noble temperament—how you have transcended worldly ambitions entirely.

    Since the time of troubles, the wise scholars of this world have retreated to the grasses, seeking refuge from momentary calamity. Yet how many have been seduced by fame and fortune, causing the mountain spirits to turn back the carriages of the worldly! But you, sir—perceiving the signs, you have acted. You tread the path beyond convention, disdaining rank and station, adhering to mountains and forests with steadfast heart. A thousand pieces of gold cannot hire your talents; ten thousand chariots cannot bend your integrity. Truly, you embody those "bright and wise who preserve themselves."

    Once, Yin Shenyuan withdrew to Mount Kuanglu. Called upon repeatedly, he never emerged. In those days, people divined the rise and fall of the realm by whether he came forth or not. Now some say: if you do not emerge, what will become of the people? Yet this is like the auspicious star and propitious clouds—when they appear, all rush forward to glimpse them. But you hold the great vessel, preserve the great way, pillow your head on stone, rinse your mouth with flowing streams, and rest on high without descending. Such clarity of spirit, such loftiness of principle—since Bo Yi and Shu Qi, there has been but one such person.

    I often wish to shake off my robes and depart to follow in your footsteps. Longing for your virtue consumes even my dreams. I have also heard that your region possesses fair lands and pleasant climate, where superior men and worthies gather to dwell. I myself have purchased a plot of land there, hoping to settle and end my days in peace—such is my quiet aspiration. I ask only for your understanding.

    I, Lim Chun of Xiangyang, am a seeker of the Way. Now, as Junggun returns, I have composed a poem to send you, wishing to observe where your aspirations truly lie. The year draws to its close; the mountain villages grow bitter with cold. I humbly pray that beyond your devotion to the Way, you will cherish your health, that my distant wishes may be fulfilled.

    With much reverence and repeated bows.
  footnotes:
    - Yi Dam-ji (李湛之) is the ostensible addressee; Lim Chun writes on his behalf to Privy Councillor Kwon, likely a hermit-scholar who has withdrawn from public service.
    - Yin Shenyuan (殷深源) and Mount Kuanglu (匡廬山) refer to historical precedents of virtuous recluses whose refusal to serve was seen as portentous.
    - Bo Yi and Shu Qi were ancient sages who chose starvation on Mount Shouyang rather than serve an unjust ruler—the supreme exemplars of integrity.
    - The poem mentioned was to be composed jointly and sent with this letter, serving as both artistic and philosophical testimony.
